00:00:15,700 --> 00:00:16,500
Today,

4
00:00:16,500 --> 00:00:19,220
we're going to have our first

5
00:00:19,220 --> 00:00:21,940
encounter with what is called gauge theory.

6
00:00:24,100 --> 00:00:26,660
All of modern physics is based,

7
00:00:26,660 --> 00:00:29,240
all of modern particle physics in particular,

8
00:00:29,240 --> 00:00:31,080
and modern general relativity,

9
00:00:31,080 --> 00:00:32,860
gravity physics,

10
00:00:32,860 --> 00:00:36,060
all fundamental views of physics,

11
00:00:36,220 --> 00:00:37,020
and a great deal,

12
00:00:37,020 --> 00:00:37,700
I might add,

13
00:00:37,700 --> 00:00:38,900
in condensed matter physics.

14
00:00:39,000 --> 00:00:40,230
Not that I don't think

15
00:00:40,230 --> 00:00:41,460
that condensed matter physics is fundamental.

16
00:00:41,560 --> 00:00:42,900
I should not have made that distinction.

17
00:00:43,380 --> 00:00:45,320
But condensed matter physics,

18
00:00:45,320 --> 00:00:48,160
particle physics,

19
00:00:48,160 --> 00:00:49,780
general relativity,

20
00:00:50,879 --> 00:00:52,679
one of the most basic principles

21
00:00:52,679 --> 00:00:54,480
is the principle of gauge invariance.

22
00:00:54,620 --> 00:00:56,260
I'm sure you've all heard of it.

23
00:00:57,080 --> 00:00:58,940
You probably wonder what it is.

24
00:00:59,240 --> 00:01:00,760
Some of you may know what it is.

25
00:01:02,020 --> 00:01:09,300
We're going to begin with our study of gauge symmetry,

26
00:01:09,300 --> 00:01:11,280
or gauge invariance,

27
00:01:11,320 --> 00:01:12,880
or gauge principle,

28
00:01:12,880 --> 00:01:15,720
by studying a simple example.

29
00:01:17,919 --> 00:01:18,600
Now,

30
00:01:18,600 --> 00:01:20,040
in 1905,

31
00:01:20,040 --> 00:01:28,340
Einstein pointed to the importance of very carefully

32
00:01:29,640 --> 00:01:31,870
defining carefully and setting up

33
00:01:31,870 --> 00:01:34,100
the idea of coordinate systems,

34
00:01:35,340 --> 00:01:40,300
that there may be some hidden assumptions that one makes

35
00:01:40,980 --> 00:01:42,900
when one speaks of things like,

36
00:01:42,900 --> 00:01:43,140
well,

37
00:01:43,140 --> 00:01:44,300
simultaneity is,

38
00:01:44,300 --> 00:01:44,600
of course,

39
00:01:44,600 --> 00:01:45,240
one of them,

40
00:01:45,860 --> 00:01:46,920
but other such things,

41
00:01:46,920 --> 00:01:48,500
the length of objects and so forth,

42
00:01:48,560 --> 00:01:51,610
and that you really do have to be very

43
00:01:51,610 --> 00:01:54,660
careful to operationally and carefully define what you mean

44
00:01:56,420 --> 00:01:58,500
by various kinds of concepts.

45
00:01:59,240 --> 00:02:00,740
Such as simultaneity,

46
00:02:00,740 --> 00:02:01,360
for example.

47
00:02:03,500 --> 00:02:06,120
Everybody thinks that they know what simultaneity means,

48
00:02:06,860 --> 00:02:12,820
but comparing times at different places is not so obvious.

49
00:02:12,840 --> 00:02:13,960
How you compare,

50
00:02:13,960 --> 00:02:16,820
how you say when two times are equal,

51
00:02:16,900 --> 00:02:19,260
when they correspond to different places,

52
00:02:19,420 --> 00:02:21,070
especially since it takes light time

53
00:02:21,070 --> 00:02:22,720
to go from one place to another.

54
00:02:23,140 --> 00:02:24,380
So he was very careful,

55
00:02:24,380 --> 00:02:26,900
and in being careful,

56
00:02:26,900 --> 00:02:28,740
he invented the special theory of relativity,

57
00:02:29,240 --> 00:02:30,580
but that,

58
00:02:30,580 --> 00:02:32,400
how shall I say,

59
00:02:32,400 --> 00:02:39,540
that idea of being careful about defining relative things

60
00:02:40,120 --> 00:02:42,440
at different places of space,

61
00:02:42,440 --> 00:02:47,120
and the ambiguities that could inherently be there,

62
00:02:47,650 --> 00:02:49,465
because you're trying to

63
00:02:49,465 --> 00:02:51,280
compare things at different locations,

64
00:02:51,700 --> 00:02:59,080
that theme has sort of permeated physics since Einstein,

65
00:02:59,240 --> 00:02:59,760
and that's what we're trying to do with Einstein's time.

66
00:03:01,180 --> 00:03:04,100
The general theory of relativity makes it even worse,

67
00:03:04,320 --> 00:03:08,460
that not only can't you compare detailed simultaneity,

68
00:03:08,500 --> 00:03:10,320
but you can't even compare,

69
00:03:10,320 --> 00:03:11,060
for example,

70
00:03:11,060 --> 00:03:12,280
in an obvious way,

71
00:03:12,440 --> 00:03:14,160
what you might mean by,

72
00:03:14,740 --> 00:03:17,000
my finger is pointing that way,

73
00:03:17,000 --> 00:03:18,160
over here,

74
00:03:18,380 --> 00:03:20,560
you point your finger in some direction,

75
00:03:20,660 --> 00:03:22,000
I point your finger in some direction,

76
00:03:22,000 --> 00:03:22,320
good.

77
00:03:22,460 --> 00:03:23,710
Are we pointing our fingers

78
00:03:23,710 --> 00:03:24,960
in the same direction or not?

79
00:03:25,280 --> 00:03:26,080
How do we tell?

80
00:03:26,280 --> 00:03:26,680
Well,

81
00:03:26,680 --> 00:03:27,180
we're looking,

82
00:03:27,180 --> 00:03:29,100
and in looking we transfer photons,

83
00:03:29,240 --> 00:03:30,100
back and forth,

84
00:03:30,100 --> 00:03:30,700
and so forth,

85
00:03:30,920 --> 00:03:32,880
and so we make comparisons

86
00:03:32,880 --> 00:03:34,840
by sending photons back and forth,

87
00:03:35,020 --> 00:03:36,760
but how do we decide without,

88
00:03:36,760 --> 00:03:37,760
you know,

89
00:03:37,760 --> 00:03:40,440
without an experiment to send something back and forth,

90
00:03:40,540 --> 00:03:43,330
how do we decide whether this and this

91
00:03:43,330 --> 00:03:46,120
are really pointing in the same direction or not?

92
00:03:47,200 --> 00:03:47,660
Well,

93
00:03:47,660 --> 00:03:49,110
one way is to try to

94
00:03:49,110 --> 00:03:50,560
carefully bring this over to here,

95
00:03:50,640 --> 00:03:51,960
and see if they're pointing in the

96
00:03:51,960 --> 00:03:53,280
same direction when we line them up,

97
00:03:53,380 --> 00:03:54,920
but how do I know that in

98
00:03:54,920 --> 00:03:56,460
the process of going from here to here,

99
00:03:56,640 --> 00:03:59,220
I didn't rotate my finger?

100
00:03:59,240 --> 00:04:00,140
And,

101
00:04:00,140 --> 00:04:02,060
of course,

102
00:04:02,060 --> 00:04:03,160
in the back of our imagination,

103
00:04:03,580 --> 00:04:06,070
we imagine that there is

104
00:04:06,070 --> 00:04:08,560
located at each point of space

105
00:04:08,560 --> 00:04:12,400
an idealized coordinate reference frame

106
00:04:12,400 --> 00:04:14,709
that are oriented parallel to each other

107
00:04:14,709 --> 00:04:17,019
when we move from one place to another,

108
00:04:17,260 --> 00:04:18,620
but maybe that's a,

109
00:04:18,620 --> 00:04:26,320
maybe that's a idea that is a little too naive.

110
00:04:26,480 --> 00:04:29,220
Maybe we have to be more careful in comparing things.

111
00:04:29,240 --> 00:04:30,060
Now,

112
00:04:30,060 --> 00:04:31,740
we compare all kinds of things,

113
00:04:32,540 --> 00:04:35,100
but the specific thing I want to talk about

114
00:04:35,100 --> 00:04:40,100
is comparing the phase of complex wave fields.

115
00:04:40,800 --> 00:04:46,160
A very important example of comparisons at different points

116
00:04:46,160 --> 00:04:48,920
has to do with complex wave fields.

117
00:04:49,100 --> 00:04:49,260
Now,

118
00:04:49,260 --> 00:04:50,040
remember,

119
00:04:50,040 --> 00:04:51,340
complex wave,

120
00:04:51,340 --> 00:04:53,220
complex fields,

121
00:04:53,500 --> 00:04:54,800
we've discussed them,

122
00:04:54,960 --> 00:04:57,720
I called a field phi,

123
00:04:59,700 --> 00:05:01,440
when it happened to be

124
00:05:01,440 --> 00:05:03,180
made out of two real components,

125
00:05:04,320 --> 00:05:06,660
phi one plus i phi two,

126
00:05:08,900 --> 00:05:09,380
and,

127
00:05:09,380 --> 00:05:09,820
of course,

128
00:05:09,820 --> 00:05:13,780
I can either think of them as complex fields

129
00:05:13,780 --> 00:05:15,940
and their complex conjugate,

130
00:05:19,340 --> 00:05:21,040
or I can just think of,

131
00:05:22,359 --> 00:05:22,840
incidentally,

132
00:05:22,840 --> 00:05:24,820
this phi and this phi are the same thing.

133
00:05:24,980 --> 00:05:26,600
I sometimes draw it this way

134
00:05:26,600 --> 00:05:28,220
and sometimes draw it this way.

135
00:05:30,260 --> 00:05:32,650
That's one way of thinking of

136
00:05:32,650 --> 00:05:35,040
a complex field as a complex field.

137
00:05:35,320 --> 00:05:37,070
The other way of thinking about

138
00:05:37,070 --> 00:05:38,820
it is a pair of real fields,

139
00:05:38,980 --> 00:05:40,510
in which case we would

140
00:05:40,510 --> 00:05:42,040
say at every point in space

141
00:05:42,040 --> 00:05:44,640
we have a set of axes,

142
00:05:45,219 --> 00:05:47,360
one of which we call phi one,

143
00:05:48,000 --> 00:05:49,760
and one of which we call phi two,

144
00:05:49,980 --> 00:05:52,000
and at every point in space,

145
00:05:52,300 --> 00:05:54,360
the field takes on some value.

146
00:05:55,100 --> 00:05:56,760
At this point over here,

147
00:05:56,880 --> 00:05:58,520
the field might be oriented,

148
00:05:59,240 --> 00:06:02,520
our complex scalar field might be located at this point.

149
00:06:02,980 --> 00:06:04,220
At that point over here,

150
00:06:04,300 --> 00:06:05,700
it might be located at this point.

151
00:06:06,719 --> 00:06:09,160
But in saying something like that,

152
00:06:09,260 --> 00:06:10,600
we're implicitly assuming

153
00:06:11,180 --> 00:06:12,800
that there's some kind of way

154
00:06:12,800 --> 00:06:16,680
of relating directions in this space

155
00:06:17,180 --> 00:06:18,900
at different points of space.

156
00:06:20,660 --> 00:06:21,220
Let's,

157
00:06:21,220 --> 00:06:22,450
just to get this idea

158
00:06:22,450 --> 00:06:23,680
and to pin this idea down,

159
00:06:24,240 --> 00:06:26,180
let's go back to the jump rope analogy.

160
00:06:26,180 --> 00:06:29,120
The jump rope analogy for the complex field

161
00:06:29,120 --> 00:06:30,600
is just that we have a string,

162
00:06:30,600 --> 00:06:31,260
a long string,

163
00:06:31,420 --> 00:06:31,960
could be a rope,

164
00:06:32,920 --> 00:06:35,380
and that rope is at every point

165
00:06:35,820 --> 00:06:38,900
free to move in two directions,

166
00:06:39,580 --> 00:06:41,820
up and down and right and left,

167
00:06:41,920 --> 00:06:43,220
from my perspective over here.

168
00:06:43,300 --> 00:06:44,280
I should have brought in a rope.

169
00:06:44,420 --> 00:06:44,620
I always,

170
00:06:44,620 --> 00:06:44,940
ah.

171
00:06:50,280 --> 00:06:51,460
Who wants to play jump rope?

172
00:06:52,720 --> 00:06:53,120
Yeah,

173
00:06:53,120 --> 00:06:53,400
okay,

174
00:06:53,400 --> 00:06:53,580
good.

175
00:06:54,160 --> 00:06:54,760
I don't know,

176
00:06:54,760 --> 00:06:57,020
this is not going to go very far.

177
00:06:57,120 --> 00:06:58,480
All we're going to do is swing the rope around,

178
00:06:58,660 --> 00:06:59,220
but okay,

179
00:06:59,220 --> 00:07:00,160
let's do it anyway.

180
00:07:01,200 --> 00:07:01,640
Yeah,

181
00:07:01,640 --> 00:07:02,900
you take that in.

182
00:07:02,960 --> 00:07:03,080
Good,

183
00:07:03,080 --> 00:07:03,360
okay.

184
00:07:03,680 --> 00:07:05,540
So this is a rope,

185
00:07:05,580 --> 00:07:07,260
which when we're stretched out is like this,

186
00:07:07,400 --> 00:07:09,200
but it's actually free to move

187
00:07:09,200 --> 00:07:10,620
both horizontally and vertically,

188
00:07:11,120 --> 00:07:13,980
and then it has the capacity not just to vibrate,

189
00:07:14,120 --> 00:07:16,260
but to vibrate in a

190
00:07:16,260 --> 00:07:18,400
way that has some angular momentum.

191
00:07:19,080 --> 00:07:19,520
Now,

192
00:07:19,520 --> 00:07:23,040
in order to explain what,

193
00:07:23,260 --> 00:07:24,000
not to explain,

194
00:07:24,100 --> 00:07:24,740
but in order to do this,

195
00:07:24,760 --> 00:07:27,180
to describe the configuration of this string,

196
00:07:27,480 --> 00:07:29,590
I have to tell you not

197
00:07:29,590 --> 00:07:31,700
just how far from the origin,

198
00:07:31,900 --> 00:07:33,700
the origin now means the straight string

199
00:07:33,700 --> 00:07:34,980
when it's as straight as possible,

200
00:07:35,460 --> 00:07:35,840
how,

201
00:07:35,840 --> 00:07:37,800
not only how far it's been displaced,

202
00:07:37,940 --> 00:07:39,600
but at what angle it's been displaced.

203
00:07:40,840 --> 00:07:43,180
So I have to describe both,

204
00:07:44,260 --> 00:07:47,780
either a complex number at every point,

205
00:07:48,000 --> 00:07:50,280
complex number could be x plus i y

206
00:07:50,280 --> 00:07:51,620
for the position of the string,

207
00:07:52,140 --> 00:07:52,620
or,

208
00:07:52,620 --> 00:07:53,300
thank you,

209
00:07:53,300 --> 00:07:57,720
or I could describe it either a pair of coordinates,

210
00:07:57,820 --> 00:07:58,760
a complex number,

211
00:07:59,080 --> 00:08:01,560
or an angle and a radius,

212
00:08:01,860 --> 00:08:04,120
any number of ways of describing it.

213
00:08:04,520 --> 00:08:07,640
But it's implicit in compa-

214
00:08:07,640 --> 00:08:09,540
implicit in describing things

215
00:08:10,290 --> 00:08:12,860
that the coordinate axes x and y

216
00:08:12,860 --> 00:08:14,560
that I use over here on the string

217
00:08:14,560 --> 00:08:17,960
are parallel to the coordinate axis over here,

218
00:08:18,020 --> 00:08:20,000
or parallel to the coordinate axis over here.

219
00:08:20,600 --> 00:08:22,860
So we have made an assumption

220
00:08:22,860 --> 00:08:25,680
that it is possible to compare angles

221
00:08:25,680 --> 00:08:28,060
at different points and say whether they're the same

222
00:08:28,060 --> 00:08:28,880
or not the same.

223
00:08:30,180 --> 00:08:32,419
It is not completely obvious

224
00:08:32,419 --> 00:08:33,880
that that's a good assumption.

225
00:08:35,000 --> 00:08:35,940
In fact,

226
00:08:35,940 --> 00:08:37,559
really honestly,

227
00:08:37,940 --> 00:08:40,720
when one takes general relativity into account

228
00:08:40,720 --> 00:08:42,760
in the motion of strings and so forth,

229
00:08:42,980 --> 00:08:44,760
it is not so obvious,

230
00:08:44,780 --> 00:08:45,900
and in fact it's not even true,

231
00:08:46,040 --> 00:08:48,400
that there's a unique way of comparing angles

232
00:08:48,400 --> 00:08:49,080
at different places.

233
00:08:49,280 --> 00:08:52,400
But we're not talking about angles in real space now.

234
00:08:52,400 --> 00:08:55,740
We're talking about angles in a fictitious field space,

235
00:08:56,760 --> 00:08:58,840
which is mathematically similar

236
00:08:58,840 --> 00:09:01,960
to the rotation of the jump rope,

237
00:09:02,180 --> 00:09:04,740
but we're talking about angles

238
00:09:05,400 --> 00:09:08,540
in a mathematical field space.

239
00:09:09,280 --> 00:09:12,780
And this situation comes up

240
00:09:12,780 --> 00:09:15,020
when we ask questions like,

241
00:09:15,300 --> 00:09:17,700
is the value of the complex field

242
00:09:17,700 --> 00:09:19,660
at one location the same

243
00:09:19,660 --> 00:09:21,820
as it is in another location or not?

244
00:09:22,720 --> 00:09:24,500
In order to answer that question,

245
00:09:24,660 --> 00:09:27,260
we have to compare angles in this,

246
00:09:27,340 --> 00:09:28,180
among other things,

247
00:09:28,340 --> 00:09:30,560
angles in this space at different points.

248
00:09:31,420 --> 00:09:32,600
Now here's what we know.

249
00:09:32,660 --> 00:09:33,840
For some field theories,

250
00:09:34,120 --> 00:09:35,440
for some field theories,

251
00:09:36,240 --> 00:09:39,260
namely those which have a concept of charge,

252
00:09:40,340 --> 00:09:42,660
that there is an invariance,

253
00:09:42,680 --> 00:09:43,520
a symmetry,

254
00:09:44,140 --> 00:09:45,780
and the symmetry corresponds

255
00:09:46,400 --> 00:09:50,100
to rotating the coordinates

256
00:09:50,100 --> 00:09:51,920
phi 1 and phi 2.

257
00:09:52,580 --> 00:09:54,260
Rotating them to some new direction,

258
00:09:54,420 --> 00:09:55,520
or equivalently,

259
00:09:55,560 --> 00:09:56,640
what's equivalently,

260
00:09:56,760 --> 00:10:01,220
is rotating the position of the field

261
00:10:01,220 --> 00:10:02,380
in,

262
00:10:02,380 --> 00:10:02,980
not in space,

263
00:10:03,180 --> 00:10:04,060
but in phi 1,

264
00:10:04,060 --> 00:10:04,820
phi 2 space.

265
00:10:05,020 --> 00:10:06,300
We either rotate the axes,

266
00:10:06,460 --> 00:10:09,780
or actually physically change the value of the field

267
00:10:09,780 --> 00:10:10,820
by rotating it.

268
00:10:10,900 --> 00:10:11,960
In either case,

269
00:10:12,060 --> 00:10:14,640
the coordinates of the field will change.

270
00:10:16,000 --> 00:10:16,640
So,

271
00:10:16,640 --> 00:10:17,940
we could imagine

272
00:10:17,940 --> 00:10:21,260
a symmetry transformation of the fields

273
00:10:23,560 --> 00:10:25,140
which can either,

274
00:10:25,140 --> 00:10:25,740
as I said,

275
00:10:25,740 --> 00:10:28,140
be described by physically changing the configuration,

276
00:10:28,540 --> 00:10:30,580
or just changing the coordinates

277
00:10:30,580 --> 00:10:32,280
that we use to describe the field.

278
00:10:33,600 --> 00:10:35,340
And we know how to describe that.

279
00:10:35,540 --> 00:10:37,480
We can describe it trigonometrically,

280
00:10:37,580 --> 00:10:40,060
that phi 2 prime is equal to

281
00:10:40,880 --> 00:10:42,800
cosine of an angle and so forth.

282
00:10:44,640 --> 00:10:46,600
But we can also describe it

283
00:10:46,600 --> 00:10:48,360
in complex notation very,

284
00:10:48,360 --> 00:10:49,380
very neatly.

285
00:10:49,960 --> 00:10:52,380
The transformation that comes out of it,

286
00:10:52,380 --> 00:10:54,180
corresponds to rotation of coordinates,

287
00:10:55,030 --> 00:10:56,100
can just be written

288
00:10:59,380 --> 00:11:00,720
phi prime,

289
